<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="51" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1166,1191]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[354,408,1166,1190]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Tube</emphasis>
: white, round in cross section, with smooth shiny surface (=outer hyaline layer present), with wide peristomes along entire length of tube, distance between peristomes decreasing towards distal end of tube (
<figureCitation box="[214,281,1238,1262]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[215,1363,206,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[212,1367,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Photos of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi. R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106, A—animal in the tube, B—view of an entire worm removed from its tube, C, D—view of the opercula. Scale: A— 0.5 mm, B— 1.5 mm, C, D— 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203390/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[266,281,1238,1262]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Tube entrance usually widened into peristome. Tube attached to substrate only at base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,386,1275,1299]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Branchial crown</emphasis>
: 
<number box="[402,472,1274,1298]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="19.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="18.0">18–20</number>
pairs of radioles not joined by inter-radiolar membrane and without long naked tips. Branchial eyes not visible in preserved material. Stylodes absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,301,1350,1374]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Peduncle</emphasis>
: inserted between 
<number box="[511,525,1349,1373]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="1.0">1</number>
st and 
<number box="[590,604,1349,1373]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="2.0">2</number>
nd dorsal radioles, slightly below bases of radioles, about 1.5 times as thick as radioles, smooth, circular in cross-section (
<figureCitation box="[663,730,1385,1409]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[215,1363,206,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[212,1367,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Photos of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi. R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106, A—animal in the tube, B—view of an entire worm removed from its tube, C, D—view of the opercula. Scale: A— 0.5 mm, B— 1.5 mm, C, D— 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203390/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[715,730,1385,1409]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Pair of lateral wings proximal to opercular bulb absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,322,1422,1446]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Operculum</emphasis>
: conical, covered with flat brown chitinous endplate about 1.7 mm in diameter, with one concentric ridge and central dome; separated from peduncle by conspicuous constriction (
<figureCitation box="[1095,1167,1457,1481]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[215,1363,206,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[212,1367,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6. Photos of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi. R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106, A—animal in the tube, B—view of an entire worm removed from its tube, C, D—view of the opercula. Scale: A— 0.5 mm, B— 1.5 mm, C, D— 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203390/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[1153,1167,1457,1481]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
B–D). Pseudoperculum absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,561,1529,1553]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Collar and thoracic membranes</emphasis>
: short collar with straight margin, not covering bases of radioles, not subdivided into lobes (= unlobed), of equal length all around. Thoracic membranes reaching up to the 
<number box="[1232,1246,1568,1592]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="4.0">4</number>
th chaetiger; wide until 
<number box="[209,223,1607,1631]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="2.0">2</number>
nd chaetiger, then narrowing abruptly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,278,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Thorax</emphasis>
: with seven thoracic segments, six of which uncinigerous. Collar chaetae limbate capillaries similar to those of thoracic chaetigers (
<figureCitation box="[486,556,1679,1703]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1931,1954]" captionTargetBox="[309,1277,206,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[301,1296,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. SEM of chaetae and uncini of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi, R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106. A—collar chaetae, B—thoracic chaetae with Apomatus - chaetae, C—thoracic uncini, D—abdominal uncini, E—abdominal chaeta. Scale: A, B— 10 μm, C, D— 5 μm, E— 2 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203391/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[542,556,1679,1703]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
A), special collar chaetae absent. 
<taxonomicName box="[948,1060,1679,1703]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Apomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[948,1060,1679,1703]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Apomatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
chaetae present (
<figureCitation box="[1263,1334,1679,1703]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1931,1954]" captionTargetBox="[309,1277,206,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[301,1296,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. SEM of chaetae and uncini of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi, R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106. A—collar chaetae, B—thoracic chaetae with Apomatus - chaetae, C—thoracic uncini, D—abdominal uncini, E—abdominal chaeta. Scale: A, B— 10 μm, C, D— 5 μm, E— 2 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203391/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[1319,1334,1679,1703]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Sawshaped thoracic uncini with six teeth above pointed anterior fang (
<figureCitation box="[891,959,1715,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1931,1954]" captionTargetBox="[309,1277,206,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[301,1296,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. SEM of chaetae and uncini of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi, R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106. A—collar chaetae, B—thoracic chaetae with Apomatus - chaetae, C—thoracic uncini, D—abdominal uncini, E—abdominal chaeta. Scale: A, B— 10 μm, C, D— 5 μm, E— 2 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203391/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[944,959,1715,1739]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,303,1751,1775]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Abdomen</emphasis>
: uncini similar to thoracic ones, but smaller and with teeth arranged in two rows above simple, distally rounded anterior peg (
<figureCitation box="[456,523,1787,1811]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1931,1954]" captionTargetBox="[309,1277,206,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[301,1296,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. SEM of chaetae and uncini of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi, R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106. A—collar chaetae, B—thoracic chaetae with Apomatus - chaetae, C—thoracic uncini, D—abdominal uncini, E—abdominal chaeta. Scale: A, B— 10 μm, C, D— 5 μm, E— 2 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203391/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[508,523,1787,1811]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
D). Chaetae flat geniculate, with rounded teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1062,1129,1787,1811]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1931,1954]" captionTargetBox="[309,1277,206,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[301,1296,193,1922]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. SEM of chaetae and uncini of Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi, R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6106. A—collar chaetae, B—thoracic chaetae with Apomatus - chaetae, C—thoracic uncini, D—abdominal uncini, E—abdominal chaeta. Scale: A, B— 10 μm, C, D— 5 μm, E— 2 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203391/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[1114,1129,1787,1811]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" box="[197,934,1823,1847]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,242,1824,1847]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Size</emphasis>
: body up to 
<quantity box="[383,462,1823,1847]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="16.0">16 mm</quantity>
long, branchial crown length up to 
<quantity box="[862,929,1824,1847]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" box="[197,403,1859,1883]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis box="[197,276,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Colour</emphasis>
: unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1022,1894,1919]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" box="[197,1022,1894,1919]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,1894,1919]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Distribution.</emphasis>
Kurile-Kamchatka Trench, Aleutian Trench, 
<quantity box="[860,1018,1895,1919]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.08" metricValueMax="4.55" metricValueMin="3.61" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="4080.0" valueMax="4550.0" valueMin="3610.0">3610–4550 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,950,2027]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,838]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="52" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1931,1955]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Remarks.</emphasis>
This is the second record of this species previously known only from a single specimen (the 
<typeStatus pageId="8" pageNumber="51">holotype</typeStatus>
) collected from the Kurile-Kamchatka. 
<taxonomicName box="[656,939,1967,1991]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="zibrowiusi">
<emphasis box="[656,939,1967,1991]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clearly differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Zibrowius, 1973" authorityName="Zibrowius" authorityYear="1973" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="challengeri">
<emphasis box="[1175,1336,1967,1991]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="51">B. challengeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zibrowius" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" refString="Zibrowius, H. W. (1973) Revision of some Serpulidae (Annelida, Polychaeta) from abyssal depths in the Atlantic and Pacific, collected by the &quot; Challenger &quot; and Prince of Monaco Expedition. Bulletin of British Museum of Natural History (Zoology), 24, 427 - 439." type="journal article" year="1973">
Zibrowius, 
<number box="[197,253,2003,2027]" pageId="8" pageNumber="51" value="1973.0">1973</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see above) by the details of the tube structure, the wide flaring peristomes at the distal end of the tube in the former and marked transverse ridges (not anteriorly directed peristomes) encircling the tube in the latter. The opercular endplate of 
<taxonomicName box="[394,541,188,212]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="zibrowiusi">
<emphasis box="[394,541,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">B. zibrowiusi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is chitinous, without calcareous deposits, whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[1136,1294,188,212]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="challengeri">
<emphasis box="[1136,1294,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">B. challengeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the endplate is completely covered by a flat calcareous deposit. In addition, the thoracic membranes of 
<taxonomicName box="[1155,1436,224,248]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="zibrowiusi">
<emphasis box="[1155,1436,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
extend to the 
<number box="[305,319,263,287]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="4.0">4</number>
th chaetiger, but they are supposedly much shorter in 
<taxonomicName box="[916,1076,263,287]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="challengeri">
<emphasis box="[916,1076,263,287]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">B. challengeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reaching up to the 
<number box="[1296,1310,263,287]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="2.0">2</number>
nd chaetiger according to the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Zibrowius" box="[576,761,298,322]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" refString="Zibrowius, H. W. (1973) Revision of some Serpulidae (Annelida, Polychaeta) from abyssal depths in the Atlantic and Pacific, collected by the &quot; Challenger &quot; and Prince of Monaco Expedition. Bulletin of British Museum of Natural History (Zoology), 24, 427 - 439." type="journal article" year="1973">
Zibrowius 
<number box="[701,761,298,322]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="1973.0">1973</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). However, this character is unreliable (see above) as in the material of 
<taxonomicName box="[280,439,337,361]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="challengeri">
<emphasis box="[280,439,337,361]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">B. challengeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined here thoracic membranes also reach the 
<number box="[1010,1024,337,361]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="4.0">4</number>
th chaetiger.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="52" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,838]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName authority="Fauvel, 1909" authorityName="Fauvel" authorityYear="1909" box="[197,680,373,398]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="langerhansi">
<emphasis box="[197,499,374,398]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Bathyvermilia langerhansi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Fauvel" box="[517,672,373,397]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" refString="Fauvel, P. (1909) Deuxieme note preliminaire sur les Polychetes provenant des campagnes de l'Hirondelle et de la Princesse- Alice, ou deposees dans la Musee Oceanographique de Monaco. Bulletin de l'Institute Oceanographique, 142, 1 - 76." type="journal article" year="1909">
Fauvel, 
<number box="[612,672,373,397]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="1909.0">1909</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, known from the Atlantic, has tubes with longitudinal keels (but lacking peristomes and transverse ridges), distal chitinous endplate encrusted with calcareous deposits, and thoracic membranes ending at the 
<number box="[497,511,448,472]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="3.0">3</number>
rd chaetiger. 
<taxonomicName authority="Sanfilippo, 2001" authorityName="Sanfilippo" authorityYear="2001" box="[644,1104,448,472]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="islandica">
<emphasis box="[644,912,448,472]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Bathyvermilia islandica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sanfilippo" box="[918,1104,448,472]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" refString="Sanfilippo, R. (2001) Bathyvermilia islandica (Polychaeta, Serpulidae): a new deep - water species from south of Iceland. Sarsia, 86, 177 - 182." type="journal article" year="2001">
Sanfilippo, 
<number box="[1048,1104,448,472]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1254,1336,448,472]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Iceland</collectingCountry>
has long thoracic membranes ending at the 
<number box="[540,554,488,511]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="7.0">7</number>
th chaetiger and tube with undulating peristomes. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sanfilippo" box="[1109,1309,487,511]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" refString="Sanfilippo, R. (2001) Bathyvermilia islandica (Polychaeta, Serpulidae): a new deep - water species from south of Iceland. Sarsia, 86, 177 - 182." type="journal article" year="2001">
Sanfilippo (
<number box="[1242,1301,487,511]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
provided a key to all four species of 
<taxonomicName box="[437,596,523,547]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[437,596,523,547]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Bathyvermilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known at that time. 
<taxonomicName box="[829,1084,523,547]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="eliasoni">
<emphasis box="[829,1084,523,547]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Bathyvermilia eliasoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(recently transferred from 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Vermiliopis</emphasis>
by Kupriyanova &amp; Nishi 
<number box="[538,596,559,583]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="2010.0">2010</number>
) also has very characteristic tube with three denticulate longitudinal keels (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,595,619]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1845,1868]" captionTargetBox="[361,1236,207,1824]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[340,1238,195,1835]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5. Line drawings of Hyalopomatus jirkovi. A—dorsal and B—lateral views of the holotype, H—operculum of holotype (redrawn from Kupriyanova 1993 a). Line drawings of Hyalopomatus sikorskii. C, D—opercula of the specimens from R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 4131, E—dorsal and F—lateral views of the holotype (redrawn from Kupriyanova 1993 a), G—operculum of the holotype (redrawn from Kupriyanova 1993 a). Bathyvermilia eliasoni, I—fragment of the tube from R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 3150 (Bailey-Brock). Filogranula stellata, J—fragment of the tube from R / V “ Vityaz ” Stn. 6348 - 2 (Bailey-Brock). Scale: A, B— 1 mm, C, D— 0.2 mm, E, F— 0.5 mm, G— 0.2 mm, H— 0.3 mm, I— 1 mm, J— 3 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/203389/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,227,595,619]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="5.0">
<date box="[212,227,595,619]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">5</date>
</number>
</figureCitation>
I).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,838]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName box="[197,479,631,655]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="zibrowiusi">
<emphasis box="[197,479,631,655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">Bathyvermilia zibrowiusi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be most similar to the recently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Bastida-Zavala, 2008" authorityName="Bastida-Zavala" authorityYear="2008" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kupriyanovae">
<emphasis box="[1068,1253,631,655]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">B. kupriyanovae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bastida-Zavala" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" refString="Bastida-Zavala, J. R. (2008) Serpulids (Annelida: Polychaeta) from the Eastern Pacific, including a brief mention of Hawaiian serpulids. Zootaxa, 1722, 1 - 61." type="journal article" year="2008">
Bastida-Zavala, 
<number box="[151,207,670,694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
that also has tubes with wide peristomes and thoracic membranes extending to the 
<number box="[1141,1155,670,694]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="4.0">4</number>
th chaetiger. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bastida-Zavala" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" refString="Bastida-Zavala, J. R. (2008) Serpulids (Annelida: Polychaeta) from the Eastern Pacific, including a brief mention of Hawaiian serpulids. Zootaxa, 1722, 1 - 61." type="journal article" year="2008">
Bastida-Zavala (
<number box="[200,259,706,730]" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" value="2008.0">2008</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
stated that the main differences between the two species is in the distal opercular plate with developed concentric ridges in 
<taxonomicName box="[383,531,742,766]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="zibrowiusi">
<emphasis box="[383,531,742,766]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">B. zibrowiusi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as opposed to simple chitinous endplate with some calcareous inclusions in 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="9" pageNumber="52" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kupriyanovae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="52">B. kupriyanovae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Other differences between these species are rather subtle (and likely unreliable), such as smooth versus wrinkled sides of opercula and relative thickness of the opercular peduncles and radioles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
